I tested the validator code for the dataset preloader and found again something that I had encountered before but not bothered looking into; the fact that that the current implementation is not safe for loading multiple dataset batches at the same time.

The preloader logic as it currently stands in my branch look sound since the task is running in the backgrond. The idea is that we can call preload(), which will asyncly  prepare data in the background, and when we need it we will check if the preload is finished, if not, we await it on the time thats left of the task.
However, during testing, I found: if we call preload twice in parallel, things break. The problem comes from the fact that the dataset loader class uses both a class variable cache and a disk cache.
If two loaders are instantiated at the same time, they both access and modify these shared caches, leading to weird stuff

I propose 3 ideas, though i think they should perhaps be separate PRs.

# 1.Make caching instance-specifc
Move all cache-related variables to init, making them part of the instance rather than the class.
This way, R2DatasetLoader operates independently and allowing parall loading. 

# 2.Implement a queue system for dataset loading
Instead of allowing multiple loaders to run in parallel, create a queue like structure that ensures only one loader exists at a time. This shouldnt be too hard, and will not change to much logic of the R2DatasetLoader.

The validator main loop would manage the queue, adding 4 new load tasks each window and poll (and delete) when used, each dataset will run in series.
We can also ensure that each dataset is prepared at least one window in advance.

# 3. A third approach i just thought about would be to batch all pages into one task per window. Then we will not need parallel loaders.
